<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <meta http-equiv="content-type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8">
    <title>Universal Teaching Station</title>
    <link id="light-styles" rel="stylesheet" href="Case_sheet_styles.css">
    <link id="dark-styles" rel="stylesheet" href="Case_sheet_styles_dark.css" disabled="">
    <script src="https://www.youtube.com/iframe_api"></script>
  </head>
  <body> <button id="theme-toggle" title="Toggle dark mode">🌙 Dark Mode</button>
    <h2>TEACHING STATION FRAMEWORK</h2>
    <p><i>A universal guide for conducting any examination or procedure in a
        teaching setting.</i></p>
    <!-- Phase 0: Learning Contract -->
    <!-- (Added to ensure clear objectives & tailored teaching) -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;0: Agree the Learning Agenda</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>0. Clarify Objectives &amp; Baseline</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Establish Learner Needs:</b> Ask the student what parts of the
          skill they feel least confident about.</li>
        <li><b>Set Specific Outcomes:</b> "By the end of this session you should
          be able to list the steps, demonstrate safe technique, and explain
          positive/negative findings."</li>
        <li><b>Check Prior Experience:</b> "Have you practised this on
          mannequins or patients before?"</li>
        <li><b>Identify Preferred Learning Style / Accessibility Needs:</b>
          Visual, hands‑on, verbal, etc.</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <!-- Phase 1: Pre-Procedure Protocol -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;1: Pre‑Procedure Protocol (The Setup)</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>1. Introduction &amp; Identification</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li>Greet the patient warmly.</li>
        <li>State your name and role clearly (e.g., "I'm Dr. Smith, a senior
          doctor.").</li>
        <li>Introduce the student by name and their role (e.g., "This is Alex, a
          third‑year medical student working with me today.").</li>
        <li>Confirm patient's identity (e.g., "Could you please confirm your
          full name and date of birth for me?").</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>2. Explanation &amp; Consent</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Explain the Indication:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>(e.g., "To better understand your abdominal pain, we need to
            perform an examination of your tummy.").</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Explain the Procedure:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>Clearly .....terms. Mention what the patient will feel (e.g., "I
            will be gently pressing on different parts of your abdomen. It
            shouldn't be painful, but please let me know if you feel any
            discomfort.").</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Check Contraindications:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>(Clinician to self/student) "</li>
          <li>recent surgery </li>
          <li>specific conditions to be aware of?"</li>
        </ul>
        <li><b>Gain Verbal Consent:</b> </li>
        <ul>
          <li>explicitly (e.g., "Are you happy for us to proceed with the
            examination?").</li>
        </ul>
        <!-- Added pointer: Signpost objectives to patient & student -->
        <li><b>Signpost Session Objective:</b> "We'll first demonstrate the
          technique, then answer any questions before practice."</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>3. Preparation &amp; Positioning</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Offer a Chaperone:</b> "Would you feel more comfortable if we had
          another member of staff, a chaperone, present for the examination?"</li>
        <li><b>Ensure Adequate Exposure:</b> Explain what clothing needs to be
          adjusted or removed and why. Provide a blanket or sheet to maintain
          dignity.</li>
        <li><b>Position the Patient:</b> "I'll need you to lie flat on your back
          for this. Are you comfortable in that position?" (Adjust as needed,
          e.g., pillows, angle of bed).</li>
        <li><b>Check for Pain:</b> "Before we begin, are you in any pain at the
          moment?"</li>
        <!-- Added pointers -->
        <li><b>Perform Hand Hygiene &amp; PPE:</b> Clean your hands and don
          appropriate protective equipment before contact.</li>
        <li><b>Gather &amp; Check Equipment:</b> Ensure all required tools are
          at hand (e.g., stethoscope, watch, glass of water, exam torch).</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <!-- Phase 2: The Core Task -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;2: The Core Procedure / Examination</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>4. Perform the Core Task</strong></summary>
      <p><i>(This is where the specific steps of the examination or procedure
          are performed. The instructor may demonstrate first, then allow the
          student to perform under supervision.)</i></p>
      <ul>
        <li>Example: Cardiovascular Examination</li>
        <li>Example: Inserting an IV Cannula</li>
        <li>Example: Respiratory Examination</li>
        <!-- Added pointers -->
        <li><b>Demonstrate First:</b> Instructor performs entire sequence while
          verbalising key landmarks and rationale.</li>
        <li><b>Highlight Systemic Components:</b> "Remember to inspect hands,
          eyes, and vitals as part of a complete assessment when relevant."</li>
        <li><b>Emphasise Patient Comfort:</b> Use minimal pressure, explain each
          step, and monitor for discomfort.</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <!-- Phase 3: Instructional Dialogue -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;3: Instructional Dialogue (For the Student)</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>5. Explain &amp; Teach</strong></summary>
      <p><i>(This dialogue occurs between the instructor and the student, while
          always maintaining respect for the patient.)</i></p>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Demonstrate Technique:</b> "Notice how I hold the stethoscope..."</li>
        <li><b>Explain Findings:</b> "We can hear a normal 'lub‑dub' sound,
          which corresponds to the first and second heart sounds. I don't hear
          any extra murmurs."</li>
        <li><b>Ask Probing Questions:</b> "Why do you think we check for a pulse
          in this location?" or "What would it mean if we found..."</li>
        <li><b>Correct Technique:</b> "Try adjusting your grip slightly like
          this for better control."</li>
        <!-- Added pointers -->
        <li><b>Teach‑Back Checks:</b> "Can you summarise the inspection points
          back to me?"</li>
        <li><b>Encourage Reflection:</b> "What part of that felt most
          challenging to you?"</li>
        <li><b>Link to Documentation:</b> "After the exam you'd record findings
          under <code>Inspection</code>, <code>Palpation</code>, <code>Percussion</code>,
          <code>Auscultation</code>."</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
    <!-- Phase 4: Post-Procedure Protocol -->
    <h3 class="h3">Phase&nbsp;4: Post‑Procedure Protocol (The Wrap‑Up)</h3>
    <details>
      <summary><strong>6. Conclusion &amp; Closure</strong></summary>
      <ul>
        <li><b>Thank the Patient:</b> "Thank you very much for your time and for
          helping us with our teaching today."</li>
        <li><b>Ensure Comfort:</b> Help the patient to get dressed or cover up.
          Ask if they are comfortable.</li>
        <li><b>Summarize Findings (to patient):</b> "Everything from that
          examination seems normal." or "Based on that, we will..."</li>
        <li><b>Address Doubts:</b> "Do you have any questions for me? (To
          patient)" ... "Do you have any questions? (To student)"</li>
        <!-- Added pointers -->
        <li><b>Agree Next Steps &amp; Practice Plan (with Student):</b> Arrange
          mannequin practice, bedside shadowing, or follow‑up assessment.</li>
        <li><b>Provide Feedback &amp; Resources:</b> Offer quick constructive
          feedback and direct the student to relevant guidelines or videos.</li>
      </ul>
    </details>
